content:
Suppose you have a set of data points $y_1, y_2, ..., y_m$ and you want to generate a scatter plot to visualize their distribution. How can you implement this in Latex?
You can use the Tikz package to create a scatter plot with the following code:
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
    only marks,
    xlabel=$x$,
    ylabel=$y$,
    nodes near coords,
    nodes near coords align={vertical},
    every node near coord/.append style={rotate=90, anchor=west}
]
\addplot[mark=*, fill=blue] coordinates {
    (data point 1)
    (data point 2)
    ...
    (data point m)
};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
Simply replace "data point 1", "data point 2", ..., "data point m" with the actual values of $y_1, y_2, ..., y_m$ to generate a scatter plot of your data set.

To create a scatter plot in LaTeX using the TikZ and PGFPlots packages, follow these steps:

1. **Include necessary packages in your preamble:**

   Ensure you include the TikZ and PGFPlots packages in your LaTeX document preamble. You can do this by adding:

   ```latex
   \usepackage{tikz}
   \usepackage{pgfplots}
   \pgfplotsset{compat=1.17} % Ensure compatibility with your version
   ```

2. **Set up your scatter plot environment:**

   Use the provided template to set up the scatter plot. You'll need to replace the placeholder text with your actual data points.

3. **Replace data points:**

   Substitute "data point 1", "data point 2", ..., "data point m" with your actual data points. If your data points are just single values and you want them plotted against an index, you need to generate (x, y) pairs. For example, if your data points are \(y_1, y_2, \ldots, y_m\), you might want to plot them as \((1, y_1), (2, y_2), \ldots, (m, y_m)\).

Here's a complete example with actual data points:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usepackage{pgfplots}
\pgfplotsset{compat=1.17}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
    only marks,
    xlabel=$x$,
    ylabel=$y$,
    nodes near coords,
    nodes near coords align={vertical},
    every node near coord/.append style={rotate=90, anchor=west}
]
\addplot[mark=*, fill=blue] coordinates {
    (1, 2.5)
    (2, 3.0)
    (3, 3.5)
    (4, 4.0)
    (5, 4.5)
    (6, 5.0)
};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

In this example, I have plotted 6 data points with x-coordinates \(1, 2, \ldots, 6\) and corresponding y-coordinates \(2.5, 3.0, \ldots, 5.0\). You can adjust the coordinates as needed to reflect your dataset. Compile this document with a LaTeX editor that supports TikZ, like TeXShop, TeXworks, or Overleaf, to view the scatter plot.
